<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Beverage-Air service</p>
    <h2>Beverage-Air: industry workhorse of mid-premium commercial refrigeration.</h2>

    <p>Beverage-Air is the workhorse of mid-premium commercial refrigeration. Manufactured in Winston-Salem, North Carolina since 1944, with a long American manufacturing history that predates the Ali Group era. Now part of Ali Group, the Italian privately-held holding company that owns roughly 25 commercial foodservice brands. The Ali Group portfolio includes Scotsman ice machines, Ice-O-Matic, Champion dishwashers, and Carpigiani gelato equipment, plus Beverage-Air refrigeration.</p>

    <p>You see Beverage-Air everywhere in LA. Chain restaurants standardize on it: Chipotle, Panera, Subway corporate accounts spec Beverage-Air across their store buildouts. Mid-tier restaurants and cafés use HR-Series reach-ins and SP-Series sandwich prep tables as their default. Convenience stores and gas stations use MR and MMR glass-door merchandisers for beverage retail. Bars use UCR and LV undercounter for back-bar storage. Hotels and chain hospitality use the full lineup.</p>

    <p>Our techs service Beverage-Air across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside. <strong>HR-Series</strong> reach-in coolers (HR1, HR2, HR3 by door count). <strong>HF-Series</strong> reach-in freezers. <strong>SP-Series</strong> sandwich prep tables and <strong>DP-Series</strong> pizza prep. <strong>UCR/UCF</strong> undercounter. <strong>MR/MMR</strong> glass-door merchandisers. <strong>LV/LVUC</strong> low-profile bar undercounter. <strong>TF/TFP</strong> back-bar coolers. <strong>WTR</strong> refrigerated worktables. <strong>HRPF</strong> pass-through reach-ins.</p>

    <p>EPA 608 Universal plus <strong>R-290 certification</strong> for the post-2018 Beverage-Air transition to propane refrigerant on many models. BHGS #A49573. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Parent context: <a href="/commercial/refrigeration/">commercial refrigeration repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 LINEUP & WHAT FAILS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Lineup and what fails</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Beverage-Air series and common service items.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Beverage-Air uses two-letter series codes by equipment category. We identify by serial number first, not just model badge.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">HR-Series Reach-In Coolers (HR1, HR2, HR3)</h3>
    <p>HR1 single-door, HR2 double-door (the most popular Beverage-Air reach-in by a wide margin), HR3 triple-door. Common in chain restaurants and mid-tier kitchens. Failure pattern in chronological order:</p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 4 to 7:</strong> Condenser fan motor seizure. Faster on coastal installs in Marina del Rey, Manhattan Beach, Newport Beach where salt accelerates bearing wear. $280 to $500.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5 to 7:</strong> Evaporator fan motor failure. Cabinet airflow stops, food warms while sensor still reads cold.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 6 to 9:</strong> Defrost timer (Paragon-style on legacy units, defrost board on modern). $200 to $340.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 3 to 5:</strong> Door gasket compression at hinge side. Beverage-Air gaskets are model-specific dimensions. $200 to $360 per door.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 8 to 12:</strong> Compressor capacitor and start relay failure. Replace as a pair.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 10 to 13:</strong> Compressor mechanical wear. This is the replace-vs-repair decision threshold on this tier.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="series-h3">HF-Series Reach-In Freezers (HF1, HF2, HF3)</h3>
    <p>Electric defrost architecture (similar to True T-49F or Turbo Air M3F, not hot-gas like Hoshizaki). Defrost heater element burnout at year 5 to 8 is the common HF-specific service item. Frost builds up, blocks airflow, freezer warms, customer calls. 2 to 3 hour repair to access the evaporator and replace the calrod element.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">SP-Series Sandwich Prep Tables</h3>
    <p>SP-Series sized by inches and door configuration (SP60HC is the 60-inch, the most common SP variant we see). Cold rail running warm is the number one SP failure. Deep evaporator clean resolves roughly 80% of those calls without parts. Lettuce, tomato, sauce, and cheese debris pack the evaporator coil over 12 to 18 months of heavy use, airflow drops, pan rail temperature climbs.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">DP-Series Pizza Prep (DP67, DP93)</h3>
    <p>Pizza-specific prep with shorter cold rail and deeper storage drawers. DP67 is 67-inch, DP93 is 93-inch. Same diagnostic patterns as SP plus drawer slide service on drawer variants. Slides corrode in coastal and humid environments.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">UCR / UCF Undercounter (UCR27, UCR48)</h3>
    <p>UCR27 single-door 27-inch, UCR48 48-inch (single section, two-drawer or two-door). UCF freezer variants. Common in food trucks, small kitchens, mid-tier restaurants. Coastal salt and tight installation airflow are the limiting factors.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">MR / MMR / MMF Glass-Door Merchandisers</h3>
    <p>MR23 (23-inch single-door), MR45 (45-inch double-door), MMR45 and larger MMR variants. Display refrigeration with glass doors. Anti-condensation heater wire failures at year 5 to 8 are the common merchandiser service item. MMF freezer variants for ice cream display and frozen food retail.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">LV / LVUC Low-Profile and TF/TFP Back-Bar</h3>
    <p>LV24 and LVUC variants are compact bar back-bar configurations. TF/TFP series are bar-side bottle coolers and beer dispensers (TF52 is the 52-inch three-door back-bar). Bar splash damage cleanup is a typical service item on these. Sticky drink residue gets into electrical components and corrodes connectors over time.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">WTR Refrigerated Worktables and HRPF Pass-Through</h3>
    <p>WTR drawer-style worktable refrigeration for pizza prep stations and sushi prep. HRPF and HRP pass-through reach-ins for hospitality and institutional kitchens (door on each side, used between line and prep). EBR emergency bottle refrigerators for specialty applications.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 TYPICAL SCENARIOS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Common scenarios</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Top Beverage-Air repairs in our 5-county territory.</h2>

    <p>In rough order of frequency on Beverage-Air service calls:</p>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Condenser fan motor replacement.</strong> The most common Beverage-Air repair across all series. Beverage-Air OEM via Ali Group North American distribution.</li>
      <li><strong>Cold rail evaporator deep clean (SP/DP prep tables).</strong> The most common prep table issue across all brands, not just Beverage-Air. Often no parts needed once the coil is clean.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket replacement.</strong> Beverage-Air specific gasket dimensions. Model-specific. We carry common HR-Series and SP-Series profiles on the van.</li>
      <li><strong>Defrost heater element (HF freezer variants).</strong> Electric defrost calrod element. 2 to 3 hour repair to access the evaporator.</li>
      <li><strong>Defrost timer replacement.</strong> Paragon-style on legacy units, defrost control board on modern. Common van-stocked timers.</li>
      <li><strong>Evaporator fan motor.</strong> Smaller cabinet motor. Cabinet airflow loss.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor capacitor and start relay.</strong> Pair replacement on aged compressors.</li>
      <li><strong>Glass-door anti-condensation heater (MR/MMR merchandisers).</strong> Heater wire in glass frame replacement. Year 5 to 8 typical.</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak repair plus recharge.</strong> EPA 608 leak detection, brazed repair, evacuate, recharge. R-290 systems require R-290 certification.</li>
      <li><strong>Bar splash component cleanup (TF/TFP, LV).</strong> Sticky drink residue in electrical harness. Cleanup, sometimes connector replacement.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Real repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Composite stories from the route.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five Beverage-Air jobs from the past 90 days. Models, symptoms, diagnosis, parts, time, total. Names omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see weekly.</p>

    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>West Hollywood, Beverage-Air HR2-1S two-door cooler (2018 install, R-134a)</h3>
        <p>Chain restaurant. Temperature climbing during dinner service. Diagnosed: condenser fan motor seized plus door gasket compressed (common combination at 6 years). Replaced motor and gasket. Total: $120 plus $385 parts plus 1.5 hours = $580. Tracked through chain corporate facilities account ticket system.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Pasadena, Beverage-Air SP60HC sandwich prep (2019 install)</h3>
        <p>Sandwich shop. Cold rail at 47°F at lunch. Diagnosed: evaporator fouled with lettuce and tomato debris. Deep cleaned the coil, cleared the drain line. Pan rail back to 38°F in 90 minutes. No parts needed. Total: $120 plus 1.5 hours = $360.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Santa Monica, Beverage-Air MMR45 merchandiser (2016 install)</h3>
        <p>Gas station convenience store. Left zone fogging the glass. Diagnosed: anti-condensation heater wire open-circuited at the lower-left corner of the glass frame. Replaced glass-frame heater. Total: $120 plus $360 part plus 2 hours = $660.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Beverly Hills, Beverage-Air DP67 pizza prep (2015 install)</h3>
        <p>Pizza shop. Cold rail temp climbing plus drawer #2 sliding rough. Diagnosed: combination of fouled evaporator and drawer slide corrosion. Deep cleaned the evap, replaced the slide assembly on drawer #2. Total: $120 plus $310 slide plus 2.5 hours = $640.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Marina del Rey, Beverage-Air TF52 back-bar 3-door bottle cooler (2017 install)</h3>
        <p>Hotel back-bar. Left section warming. Diagnosed: refrigerant leak at evaporator brazed joint plus sticky drink residue throughout the electrical harness. EPA 608 leak repair: pumped down, brazed coil repair, evacuated to 500 microns, recharged R-134a to nameplate. Cleaned the electrical harness with appropriate solvent. Total: $120 plus $480 refrigerant plus $720 labor = $1,320.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we do for Beverage-Air, and what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong></p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Full HR-Series reach-in coolers (HR1, HR2, HR2-1S, HR3 plus all variants)</li>
      <li>HF-Series reach-in freezers (HF1, HF2, HF3)</li>
      <li>SP-Series and DP-Series prep tables (sandwich and pizza configurations)</li>
      <li>MTP and SPED alternate prep configurations</li>
      <li>UCR / UCF undercounter (refrigerator and freezer, all sizes including UCR27 and UCR48)</li>
      <li>MR / MMR / MMF glass-door merchandisers (MR23, MR45, MMR45 and larger)</li>
      <li>LV / LVUC low-profile bar undercounter</li>
